### 4.2 Views (Pre-written JOINs)

Views are like **saved queries**. Instead of writing a complex JOIN every time, we define it once as a view and simply call `SELECT * FROM view_name`.

#### `vw_DriveDetails`
Joins [Drives](file:///c:/Users/Aadithya/OneDrive/Desktop/dbms%20mini/frontend/drives.html#168-180) + `Companies` to produce one rich row per drive with the company name, logo, and total applicant count (a **subquery** inside the view).
```sql
SELECT d.*, c.Name AS CompanyName, c.LogoInitial, c.LogoColor,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Applications WHERE DriveID = d.DriveID) AS TotalApplications
FROM Drives d JOIN Companies c ON d.CompanyID = c.CompanyID
```

#### `vw_StudentDashboard`
Joins [Applications](file:///c:/Users/Aadithya/OneDrive/Desktop/dbms%20mini/frontend/dashboard.html#302-340) + [Drives](file:///c:/Users/Aadithya/OneDrive/Desktop/dbms%20mini/frontend/drives.html#168-180) + `Companies` to give a student a full view of their applied drives with company name, role, and status.

#### `vw_AdminDashboard`
A single row of aggregate stats for the admin panel:
- Total registered students
- Active drives count  
- Total students placed (Accepted status)
- Total applications

These use **scalar subqueries** (`SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ... WHERE ...`) — four separate subqueries all collapsed into one row.

